  "prompt": "Can tax exemption be availed on tax saving FD for the entire tenure of 5 years by investing 1.5 lakhs in the 1st year?",
  "response": "In India, tax-saving fixed deposits (FDs) are eligible for tax deductions under Section 80C of the Income Tax Act. When you invest in a tax-saving FD, you can claim a deduction of up to \u20b91.5 lakh in the financial year in which the investment is made. However, this deduction is subject to the overall limit of \u20b91.5 lakh available under Section 80C, which includes other eligible investments and expenses.\n\nThe key points to note regarding tax-saving FDs are:\n\n1. **One-Time Deduction**: The tax deduction can only be availed in the year when the investment is made. If you invest \u20b91.5 lakh in a tax-saving FD in a particular financial year, you can claim the deduction in that year only.\n\n2. **Lock-in Period**: Tax-saving FDs have a lock-in period of 5 years, during which you cannot withdraw the funds. However, tax benefits are not available for each year of the tenure.\n\n3. **Interest Taxability**: The interest earned on tax-saving FDs is taxable. The bank may deduct TDS (Tax Deducted at Source) on this interest, and you will need to declare the interest income in your tax returns in the year it is credited to your account.\n\nIn summary, you can claim a tax deduction for the investment amount in the first year up to the limit of \u20b91.5 lakh under Section 80C, but you cannot avail of deductions for the same investment in subsequent years. The interest income earned during the tenure will be taxable each year.",
